The Americas
----------------
[1] Ecuador (El Oro)
Date: Mon 10 Oct 2011
Source: Diario Opinion [in Spanish, trans. Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ, edited]
http://www.diariopinion.com/primeraPlana/verArticulo.php?id=809978


El Oro is one of the provinces in which measles infection has been
ruled out, hence health authorities have implemented an
epidemiological barrier in order to protect the population.

Although the epidemic re-emerged in the province of Tungurahua, where
82 suspected and 22 confirmed cases have been reported, the Ministry
of Public Health (MSP) has deployed several medical teams to control
the disease and prevent its spread. Cases have also been reported in
Pastaza, Cotopaxi, and Los Rios.

As of Monday of last week [3 Oct 2011], the Provincial Directorate of
Health of El Oro has reported 68 cases of measles in the provinces
mentioned, of which 28 have been confirmed by the INH [National
Institute of Health]-Quito laboratory and 2 identified with genotype
B3, which exists in Africa and the USA.

All these cases were recorded in the communities of Atahualpa, Huachi
Chico, Huachi Loreto, Huachi Totoras, La Merced, Raisin, Pelileo
Pilahuin, Montalvo, and Quisapincha. 58 patients have been
hospitalized, and 10 have remained with home isolation.

The majority of cases (53, 78 percent) have been reported in the
community of Quisapincha, with the other communities registering
between 1-2 cases. The age group with the highest number of cases
reported are children of less than one year (27, 39.7 percent).

There are 51 cases (75 percent) with no MMR [measles, mumps, rubella]
vaccination. Cases were reported during epidemiological weeks 28, 29,
35, 37-39, with most notifications during weeks 38 and 39.

A press release from the Ministry of Public Health [MSP] indicates
that no cases of measles have been reported in Ecuador since 1996 and
that the country, like other countries in the Americas, is working
hard to eradicate measles, rubella, and polio.

In April 2011, the PAHO-WHO alert and response centers declared an
epidemic alert in the region of the Americas because of the increase
in the number of measles cases imported from the United States or from
endemic countries such as in Africa. During week 37 (17 Sep 2011),
1005 cases of measles were reported in the Americas, distributed in
several countries across the continent. Therefore, the MSP [of
Ecuador] initiated a contingency plan which included vaccination of
the population.

The last cases of indigenous measles viral infection in Ecuador were
reported in 1996. The Region of the Americas declared the interruption
of endemic transmission of measles in 2000. However, the persistence
of the virus in countries in other regions constitutes a threat
because of the presence of imported virus. As of epidemiological week
38, PAHO-WHO reported a total of 1015 cases of measles in the Region
of the Americas.

In July 2011, the Ministry of Health of Ecuador surveillance system
for acute febrile illnesses with acute non-vesicular rash identified
the 1st 2 cases of importation-related measles. On 31 Aug 2011, a new
case of measles was detected in Ambato canton, community of
Quisapincha, and since then, there have been secondary cases of the
disease.

Due to the implementation of the alert and the strengthening of the
epidemiological surveillance system, research has been conducted in
the provinces of Santo Domingo de los Tsachilas, Pastaza, Los Rios,
Imbabura, without any cases of the disease having been confirmed so
far.

All suspected cases have been investigated clinically and
epidemiologically, and notification of all suspected cases has been
intensified. Any suspected case outside of the outbreak area is
managed through rapid monitoring of coverage, vaccination, and
follow-up of direct contacts.

