******
[3] Ecuador (air travel control)
Date: Thu 13 Oct 2011
Source: Andes [in Spanish, machine trans. abbreviated & edited]
http://andes.info.ec/portada/controles-en-aeropuertos-para-frenar-brote-de-sarampion-en-el-pais-100865.html


On the recommendation of the Ministry of Health, all travelers leaving
or entering Ecuador will have to posses a certificate of vaccination
against measles. This proposal is being put into effect at Quito
airport, where such a certificate will be requested in the case of
adult passengers and vaccination documents in the case of children.
This measure will apply also at international airports in other
cities, taking effect from 10 Oct 2011.

However, the statement recognises that it will not be possible to
implement the requirement immediately, as this decision will have to
be approved in consultation with other countries in the region,
because Ecuador is a signatory to the International Health Regulations
governing the establishment of such measures.

In Quito, older individuals [presumably those older than those
targeted for routine vaccination activities] should go to the Health
Center 1, which is located in Rocafuerte Street in the historic centre
of the capital, to be immunized against measles virus infection. As of
yesterday [Wed 12 Oct 2011], 87 cases of measles have been confirmed.
Meanwhile, in the coastal city of Guayaquil, the 2 children admitted
to the Hospital Francisco de Icaza Bustamante -- a child of 2 years
and a 4-year-old girl -- will be discharged within the next few hours,
although the results of confirmatory tests have still to be received.
In addition, 470 workers including doctors and other employees of the
health service are receiving home care to reduce risk of spread of the
infection to the general population.

The outbreak has increased demand for vaccines in the country. As of
today [13 Oct 2011], Ecuador has 440 000 doses of vaccine in reserve.

