******
[4] Ecuador (current total)
Date: Fri 14 Oct 2011
Source: El Universo [in Spanish, machine trans. edited]
http://www.eluniverso.com/2011/10/15/1/1447/van-93-casos-sarampion-contagio-avanza.html


Three newly suspected cases of measles were diagnosed yesterday [13
Oct 2011] in the province of Guayas, where last week there were 2, one
proven by laboratory analysis to be the African B3 strain. This brings
the nationwide total number of cases to 93.

One of the new suspected case of measles was diagnosed at the
Children's Hospital of Ycaza Francisco Bustamante in Guayaquil on
Thursday afternoon [13 Oct 2011]. This is an 8 month old child, a
relative of the 2 children who were initially diagnosed by the
National Institute of Hygiene (INH). The girl referred to above had
previously been evaluated in the hospital last week following contact
with 2 [known infected] children.

The 2 other suspected cases are patients in a hospital in Milagro,
Carlos Solis, director of the health facility, told reporters. Two
children have symptoms characteristic of measles. Patient samples have
been sent to Guayaquil to confirm the identity [genotype] of the
measles virus involved.

Meanwhile, the Ministry of Health reported yesterday [13 Oct 2011]
that as of epidemiological week 41 of this year [2011], a total of 93
confirmed cases had been reported. Tungurahua leads the list with 88
cases, Pichincha 4 cases, and Guayas has one case. There are dozens of
other suspected cases, which have yet to be confirmed by laboratory
testing.

The epidemic was presented initially in the parish of Quisapincha in
Ambato in July [2011], supposedly after a tourist who had the virus
arrived in the area from Minnesota (USA).

In its latest bulletin, the Ministry of Health confirmed that a
massive national immunisation campaign will begin in November 2011.
Current activity is being conducted in 2 phases, according to the
agency. The 1st is aimed at the population aged 6 months to children
aged 4 years 11 months 29 days, and will commence all over the country
in late October 2011. The 2nd stage will target the population of
5-year-old to children aged 14 years 11 months 29 days.

Carlos Castillo, delegate from the Pan American Health Organization
for the eradication of measles, last week recommended that the
vaccination be carried out across the country before the November 2011
holiday.

